2026-04-20 15:52:12,140 - midas_agent.stdlib.plan_execute_agent - INFO -   [iter 6] Plan response (29288 tokens): I have successfully identified and fixed the bug in the separability_matrix function for nested CompoundModels.

## Problem Analysis

The issue was in the `_cstack` function in `/testbed/astropy/modeling/separable.py`. When dealing with nested compound models like `Pix2Sky_TAN() & (Linear1D(10) & Linear1D(5))`, the function was incorrectly handling the case where one of the operands was a `CompoundModel`.

In the original code, when `_cstack` was called with a `CompoundModel` as the right operand, it would try to set `cright[-right.shape[0]:, -right.shape[1]:] = 1` (line 245). However, `right` was already a numpy array from the recursive `_separable` call, not a simple integer value, so this assignment was incorrect.

## The Fix

I fixed the issue by changing line 245 in `/testbed/astropy/modeling/separable.py` from:
```python
cright[-right.shape[0]:, -right.shape[1]:] = 1
```
to:
```python
cright[-right.shape[0]:, -right.shape[1]:] = right
```

This ensures that when `right` is already a numpy array (from the recursive `_separable` call), we properly assign that array to the appropriate slice of `cright` instead of trying to assign the literal value `1`.

## Verification

I thoroughly tested the fix with:
1. The exact examples from the issue description
2. Multiple test cases with different nesting patterns
3. All existing tests in the separable module to ensure no regressions
4. Edge cases with various compound model combinations

The fix ensures that nested compound models now correctly compute their separability matrices, matching the expected behavior described in the issue. The separability matrix for `Pix2Sky_TAN() & (Linear1D(10) & Linear1D(5))` now correctly returns the same result as `Pix2Sky_TAN() & Linear1D(10) & Linear1D(5)`, which is the expected behavior.

The fix is minimal, targeted, and maintains backward compatibility while resolving the specific issue with nested compound models in the separability_matrix function.
